ğŸ¤ Interview Opening Line (BRUTE FORCE â€” ALWAYS FIRST âœ…)

â€œIâ€™ll start with a brute-force approach: Iâ€™ll generate all substrings of length k, count how many vowels each substring has, and keep track of the maximum.â€

âŒ Why Brute Force is Bad

Number of substrings of length k â†’ O(n)

Counting vowels in each substring â†’ O(k)

Total = O(n Ã— k) â†’ slow when k is large

â¡ï¸ We can optimize this.

ğŸ¤ Transition Line (IMPORTANT)

â€œSince the substring length is fixed, I can optimize this using a fixed-size sliding window.â€

âœ… Optimized Approach â€” Fixed Size Sliding Window
ğŸ§  Core Idea

Maintain a window of exactly size k

Count vowels in the first window

Slide the window:

Remove left character

Add right character

Update maximum vowel count

ğŸªŸ Window Rule
Window size must always be exactly k

ğŸ§ª Example Dry Run
s = "abciiidef", k = 3

Window	Vowels
"abc"	1
"bci"	1
"cii"	2
"iii"	3 âœ…
"iid"	2

Answer = 3

ğŸ§¾ Fully Commented C++ Code (with inline dry run)
class Solution {
public:
    int maxVowels(string s, int k) {

        int vowelCount = 0;
        int maxCount = 0;

        // Count vowels in first window of size k
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            if (isVowel(s[i]))
                vowelCount++;
        }

        maxCount = vowelCount;

        // Slide the window
        for (int right = k; right < s.size(); right++) {

            // Add new character
            if (isVowel(s[right]))
                vowelCount++;

            // Remove left character
            if (isVowel(s[right - k]))
                vowelCount--;

            maxCount = max(maxCount, vowelCount);

            /*
            Dry Run:
            right = 3 -> window "bci"
            add 'i', remove 'a'
            */
        }

        return maxCount;
    }

    bool isVowel(char c) {
        return c == 'a' || c == 'e' || c == 'i' ||
               c == 'o' || c == 'u';
    }
};

â±ï¸ Time & Space Complexity
Type	Complexity
Time	O(n)
Space	O(1)
ğŸ§  Pattern Recognition (INTERVIEW GOLD)

If problem says:

â€œsubstring of length kâ€

â€œmaximum / minimum in windowâ€

â€œfixed lengthâ€

ğŸ‘‰ Fixed-Size Sliding Window

ğŸ¤ Optimized Interview Line (Say This)

â€œThis is a fixed-size sliding window because the window length never changes; we only slide it forward.â€

ğŸ” Follow-up Interview Questions & Variants (VERY IMPORTANT)
1ï¸âƒ£ What if we want minimum number of vowels?

Same logic

Track minimum instead of maximum

2ï¸âƒ£ What if uppercase vowels are included?

Convert to lowercase or check both cases

3ï¸âƒ£ What if k > s.length()?

No valid window â†’ return 0

4ï¸âƒ£ Return the actual substring?

Track starting index of best window

